channel.description: TOI delivers the Top Latest World news and Headlines from US, UK, Gulf, Pakistan, China, Europe and rest of the world.

item.title: US general pleads guilty to 3 counts in sex case
item.description: A US army general accused of sexual assault is pleading guilty to three lesser charges, but maintains his innocence on five remaining counts.

item.title: Newsweekâ€™s print revival starts on Friday
item.description: Newsweek magazine, online only since the end of 2012, will return to print starting Friday in the United States and Europe.

item.title: Pakistan to form new panel to step up peace talks
item.description: The Pakistan government today decided to form a new committee to accelerate peace talks with the Pakistani Taliban.

item.title: Tunisia lifts emergency rule after 3 years
item.description: Tunisian President Moncef Marzouki has lifted a state of emergency in force since the 2011 uprising that triggered the Arab Spring, his office said today.

item.title: Sarkozy, Carla Bruni seek to block secret tapes
item.description: Nicolas Sarkozy and his wife Carla Bruni on Thursday launched a legal bid to prevent any further publication of tapes secretly recorded during his 2007-12 term as French president.

item.title: Egypt court suspends Morsi murder trial
item.description: An Egyptian court suspended today the murder trial of Mohamed Morsi after his lawyers requested new judges, sources said, the third such case against the deposed president to be put on hold.

item.title: Australian parents shocked as son caged in Egypt
item.description: The parents of jailed Australian journalist Peter Greste said on Thursday they were haunted and depressed by images of him caged in an Egyptian court.

item.title: Abu Dhabi airport technical failure halts flights
item.description: Gulf airline Etihad Airways say all flights into its hub of Abu Dhabi were diverted this morning due to a technical failure at the airport.

item.title: Ukraine: UN, EU hold emergency talks
item.description: Ahead of the summit, the EU froze assets held by 18 Ukrainians accused of embezzlement, including ousted Moscow-backed Yanukovych and his son Oleksandr.

item.title: Nato airstrike kills 5 Afghan soldiers: Official
item.description: A provincial government official said an early morning Nato airstrike in Afghanistan's central Logar province killed 5 Afghan National Army soldiers and wounded another 17.

item.title: Clinton blasts Putin after her Hitler remark
item.description: Russian President Vladimir Putin is a tough but thin-skinned leader who is squandering his country's potential, former US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton said on Wednesday, a day after she likened his actions on the Crimean peninsula of Ukraine to those of Adolf Hitler in the 1930s.

item.title: Venezuela breaks ties with Panama
item.description: President Nicolas Maduro announced that he would break off relations with Panama, which he accused of being a "lackey" of the US.

item.title: Osama's son-in-law Qaida chief's right-hand: Trial
item.description: The son-in-law of Osama bin Laden acted as al-Qaida leader's right-hand man and appeared alongside the terror mastermind in a propaganda video just one day after the carnage of the 9/11 attacks, US prosecutors said on Wednesday.

item.title: Osama's son-in-law Qaeda chief's right-hand
item.description: The son-in-law of Osama bin Laden acted as the Al-Qaeda leader's right-hand man and appeared alongside the terror mastermind in a propaganda video just one day after the carnage of the 9/11 attacks, US prosecutors said on Wednesday.

item.title: Osama's son-in-law Qaida chief's right-hand: Trial
item.description: The son-in-law of Osama bin Laden acted as al-Qaida leader's right-hand man and appeared alongside the terror mastermind in a propaganda video just one day after the carnage of the 9/11 attacks, US prosecutors said on Wednesday.

item.title: 1 in 3 women sexually or physically abused in EU
item.description: One in every three women in the European Union have admitted to experiencing either physical or sexual violence from the age of 15.

item.title: Migrants create highest number of jobs in UK
item.description: Britain is trying hard to clampdown on migrants entering or living in the UK. But latest data revealed on Wednesday they have created highest number of jobs in the country.

item.title: Venezuela's Chavez remembered with pomp and protests
item.description: Followers of late socialist leader Hugo Chavez flooded the streets of Venezuela on Wednesday for the anniversary of his death, an emotional but welcome distraction for his successor from violent protests raging for the last month.

item.title: TV anchorwoman criticizes Kremlin on Ukraine
item.description: An anchorwoman on a Kremlin-funded TV network said on Wednesday that she is standing by her criticism of Russia's military incursion in Ukraine.

item.title: Attacks in Baghdad area kill 21 people
item.description: Bombings mainly targeting Shiite areas of Baghdad and attacks on security force checkpoints in and around the capital killed at least 21 people Wednesday, officials said.

item.title: Pakistan resumes Taliban talks despite deadly blast
item.description: Pakistani government and Taliban negotiators resumed peace talks Wednesday and said they were ready to move to a decisive "second phase" even as a militant attack killed six military personnel.

item.title: Fighting breaks out in South Sudan army barracks
item.description: Heavy fighting broke out in the main military barracks in war-torn South Sudan's capital Juba on Wednesday, underscoring serious tensions within the national army as it battles a rebel uprising.

item.title: Venezuela marks year without Chavez amid protests
item.description: Venezuela marks one year since Hugo Chavez died on Wednesday, with his successor leading ceremonies for the "eternal comandante" whose socialist revolution is now facing persistent opposition protests.

item.title: North Korea holds parliamentary polls
item.description: North Korea, accused of human rights violations, elects its largely symbolic parliament this weekend, with leader Kim Jong-un, the third in his family dynasty to rule the totalitarian state, running unopposed in a legendary mountain district.

item.title: Britain plans 'sugar tax' to control obesity
item.description: Britain's chief medical officer has told a parliamentary committee of MPs that sugar was addictive and the introduction of a sugar tax was needed urgently.
